\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10187699 RT  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10627816\charrsid2896712 Aye, that's the same. That's the sam
e thing. Aye. Tip-cat. And - then we used to play motions. Have you ever heard of them? Well it was a money game. It was a - a - a sort of a - two sides, now then, you would have a little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5445222\charrsid2896712 confab}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10627816\charrsid2896712  - what you were going to do you see. Now the first one went a
nd he would - and he would imitate what he was doing. Plucking apples. Chopping sticks. Or anything - or anything in that description. And if they could guess exactly what you were - you were doing, or trying to do then that knocked you out from it. We us
e
d to play what was it they call that other game - where you used to jump over - on the box. On the back. There was - one used to stand with his back to the wall, and then there was other three or four - would - with their bodies bent, and the other team, 
t
he opposing team used to run and jump as far as they could you know for - all the team to - to sit astride these fellows that was down. Aye. And if they - if the chain broke well that was that. But if - if you jumped and you hadn't - your feet happened to
 touch the ground, that finished it, you were out. Yes.
